Ok, so either I, unknowingly, follow Nick Cave’s art around, or he, unknowingly, follows me around with his art. Haha. These are some of his “Soundsuits” that are largely constructed from objects he finds at flea markets or antique shops. This first one I found this week at Princeton University’s Art Museum, when my friends from San Diego were back home visiting Jersey. We haphazardly wandered in, not knowing about what an extensive and impressive collection is housed on campus, and there was a Nick Cave piece as soon as I entered. (I am embarrassed to say I’ve never been in this art museum ever in my life, and it’s right near me) This one is from 2017. The other “Soundsuit” I randomly stumbled upon while I was with my friend, Kim, in Louisville in November for just a quick stopover for brunch before taking off to Cleveland. It was located in 21c Museum and Hotel in Louisville. That piece was made in 2007.  Mr. Cave, these are beautifully crafted, and the thought process as to why you began creating them is something we should all take a moment to think about...protective garments made in the wake of the Rodney King beating in 1991, that would obscure the wearer’s identity, forcing us to look at the world without judgment.
.
.

These boxing gloves fabricated with upcycled wedding dresses are from @zoebuckman’s “Let Her Rave” series. Buckman’s work grapples with the dichotomies within femininity whether it’s between hard and soft elements which are represented in her chosen materials, or through her reconciliation of misogynistic lyrics found in beloved hip hop lyrics that she embroiders onto vintage lingerie. Zoë isn’t afraid to go there and I love her for it. 🤍

Jody Paulsen. “Find Your Gaggle.” Produced in 2019. Paulsen was born in 1987 in Capetown, South Africa where he continues to live and work. “Find Your Gaggle” is a monumental portrait collage of a brightly colored costumed group. This hand-crafted felt collage recalls the playful hobbies of childhood, a practice the artist employs to reveal and explore personal and cultural identity. Paulsen expands this into a call to action. Go find your people. Find you community. “Find Your Gaggle.”

Cracking Art Group, Red Penguin, 2005, edition of 200, 47 x 19 x 18 inches, plastic.
•
21c co-founders Laura Lee Brown and Steve Wilson discovered the Red Penguin at the 2005 Venice Biennale when they were installed across the city in conjunction with the celebrated international exhibition of contemporary. Laura Lee and Steve brought the red flock home, where they were included in the inaugural exhibition at 21c Louisville, “Hybridity.” Guests and visitors fell in love with the red penguins, prompting 21c to keep them on permanent view and to commission new penguins in a spectrum of colors for all 21c locations.
•
Cracking Art was founded in 1993 by seven artists: Alex Angi, Kicco, Renzo Nucara, Carlo Rizzeti, Omar Ronda, Marco Veronese and William Sweetlove. They have exhibited widely throughout Europe and first exhibited at 21c Museum Louisville in 2006.

It’s hard to imagine walking into a 21c Museum Hotel without encountering one of our now-synonymous Penguins, but they were never intended to remain on permanent exhibition. Cracking Art’s Red Penguin sculptures were first exhibited at 21c Louisville in 2006. 21c founders Laura Lee Brown and Steve Wilson purchased the sculptures after seeing them perched around the city at the 2005 Venice Biennale as part of a public art project.
“The public really chose the penguins,” says Wilson. “They were part of our opening exhibition in Louisville and people couldn’t help but interact with them. They would move them around, take photos with them, take them to dinner and to their rooms. They have really become an icon, and emblematic of our mission to make thought-provoking contemporary art more accessible to the public.”
13 years and 8 hotels later, each 21c has its own flock of Penguins — each in a color that embodies the singular identity of their city. The Penguins greet visitors throughout the hotel – in the lobby, elevators, restaurant, guest rooms, and often, where you least expect them. (For those looking to visit them all: 21c Bentonville, GreenPenguin; 21c Cincinnati, Yellow Penguin; 21c Durham, Fuschia Penguin; 21c Kansas City, Sky Blue Penguin; 21c Lexington, Blue Penguin; 21c Louisville, Red Penguin; 21c Oklahoma City, Purple Penguin; 21c Nashville, Teal Penguin.)

The lines and curves of @21chotels. Where each room explores a different theme about the history of the city and the region — and the furniture is as much of a statement as the art that adorns it’s walls.

Located in the basement of the 21c Hotel is The Vault. This building, Circa 1937, was a former bank. In keeping with the historical side of the building much of the original details remain. See the original bank vaults, a very unique “security system”, terrazzo flooring and beautiful mahogany wood. Stop by the Counting House restaurant when you visit for an appetizer or cocktail. 
Yes, the Counting House! See how they made good use carrying the bank theme throughout the hotel?! Oh, and while you’re touring The Vault, check out the $flooring$! Keeping history alive in creative ways brings #beauty to the #bullcity.

The iconic lights that reflect the colors of the #kansascity #sky by @luftwerk gracing the entrance of @21chotels - Linear Sky. The LEDs are programmed with a lighting sequence inspired by the changing hues of the outdoor skies above the #urban #landscape of Kansas City: the #palette of bright morning saturates the walls that greet visitors, while the glow of waning daylight colors envelop those en route to the outdoors. #LinearSky juxtaposes day and night, nature and #technology, past and present, welcoming visitors into a space of the future. .

2 oz Four 🌹 Single Barrel Bourbon
1 oz sweet potato pie batter
.75 oz lemon
2 dashes Peychauds bitters
Spritz absinthe or 2 drops
Sprinkle nutmeg
Star anise 
Orange and lemon zest
Add bourbon, sweet potato pie batter, lemon and bitters to a shaker filled with ice. Shake until your hand is really cold. Strain into a rocks glass filled with ice. Garnish with a spritz (or 2 drops) of absinthe, star anise, nutmeg and citrus peels. 🥃🍠🍋

Last week, we were invited by our besties @wafflesnwhiskey and @thetastyescape to experience the new Mary Eddy’s menu. We had SO MUCH delicious food that I can’t wait to go back and try again. Many of you know my allergy to nightshades keeps me from trying new restaurants for their food- it’s always a little nerve wrecking to see a menu full of nightshades and wonder if they can accommodate. However, the incredible team at @maryeddysokc gave me every assurance from the moment we sat down that they were ready for the challenge. 😉 There were some things that I couldn’t have, but @thehodgelab took one for the team and tried everything for me.

We had tastes of several cocktails throughout the night, but my favorite by far was the You are Enchanting, inspired by the current @21chotels exhibition Seeing Now. The drink is a twist on a whiskey sour, with the addition of orgeat and a gold shimmer.

Also featured are (in order): West Villager (whiskey, coffee syrup, amaro), Laid Back (gin, cucumber and pink peppercorn syrup, lemon), Sweet Potato Hummus, Pan Roasted Chicken, and Chocolate Torte with brittle.

Got a chance to view the current exhibit at the @21chotels Cincinnati. The exhibit, "Dress up, Speak Up: Regalia and Resistance" is on display until July. Per the display's website "whether clad in the stylized garb of Enlightenment-era Europe, the traditional coverings of ancient religious tradition, or the gender-bending bling of popular culture, these representations of self and other role-play in real time, reach back through history to address prevailing personal, social and political challenges."

The 19th Amendment is almost 100 years old. To celebrate, artist Marilyn Artus of Oklahoma City is constructing an 18x26' flag with 36 stripes to represent each of the 36 states that took part in the ratification of the 19th Amendment. She's coming to Frankfort, KY to collaborate with artist Linda Erzinger to sew her stripe for Kentucky on the flag! The Women's Suffrage Centennial Chorus will be performing at the event. 
Passed by Congress June 4, 1919, and ratified on August 18, 1920, the 19th amendment kicked open the door for women to make their voices heard. This project is non partisan- we hope you'll come and celebrate with us!

Beekman opens that vault on some of her most treasured, trade secrets exemplified by three cocktails per a class. 21c Museum Hotel
Location: 700 W. Main St.
Hours: 24/7
• 𝕗𝕣𝕖𝕖 𝕞𝕦𝕤𝕖𝕦𝕞 •

This hotel is both a hotel AND a contemporary art museum. You can’t miss the double-size gold replica of Michelangelo's statue of David right in front of the entrance. 
Unfortunately, it costs money for a hotel stay, but the museum is FREE and open 24/7 to the public, year round. So no worries about rushing out the door to get here, drink your coffee, let the kids take their time getting ready, and then take a stroll through this museum! Let me know how it goes 😉

Just landed in Michigan for Module 1 of my 300 hour yoga teacher training in Michigan! Ten straight 12 hour days. 😳 I’m incredibly excited, a bit nervous, but mostly grateful for this opportunity to train under Jonny Kest and his crew. I know it’s going to be a transformative experience, but that’s about all I know. I will miss all of the friends/family that I teach and teach along side with, but I can’t wait to be able to share the wisdom I gained once I get back! Here is the piece I worked on for most of this afternoon in my #modernquiltmasters workshop with Jacquie Gering. Her designs are so wonderfully accessible once she helps you deconstruct them! I learned so much on my own from her book “Walk” and from her @therealbluprint classes, but this workshop has really allowed me to hone my walking foot skills. We have one more half-day session left tomorrow morning, but I’ll be bringing home enough inspiration and challenge for countless quilts. I’ll also be bringing home a new 570QE from @berninausa ! Nope, I’m not giving up my @janomeamerica #janome6700p just yet, but that guy is getting a new roomie! It’s actually shipping to me from the local KC Bernina dealer so I don’t have to carry it. But the answer to the question “how do I love thee? Let me count the ways” starts with 1) the amazing Bernina walking foot, 2) an included stitch regulator for FMQ, 3) a giant capacity bobbin ... and more. OMGuacamole it’s a lovely piece of equipment! .
.
.
So, isn’t this sample cool? The entire outside grid is one continuous line, and the interior triangles are one continuous line each. Because I have some experience with these designs, I was able to do the inside triangles with almost no marking. The outside design did require a good bit of planning and marking, but stitched up quickly once the foundation was in place. I can’t wait to use these in a real life quilt..
.
.
Thanks, Jacquie! You’re the bomb! More sample pictures coming soon. .
.
.
.

When @lisaspointofview travels home to NW Arkansas, “A Must See - 21C Museum Hotel” in Bentonville is always at the top of my list to visit. 
The @21chotels is a boutique museum hotel,  located just off the Bentonville downtown square, is a destination for hotel guests, locals, and visitors alike. The outdoor art/sculpture exhibits including “Making Change 2015” and the stunning art displayed through the inside of hotel make it well worth the visit. Afterward make sure and dine or have a cocktail at the @thehivebentonville . Arkansas chef Matthew McClure creates delicious  cuisine using local ingredients for an amazing dining experience. 
Click on the link in my BIO to read about my visit last year. COVID-19 hit much of the world like a ton of bricks, so this sculpture by Hector Zamora seemed an appropriate photo to share on International Sculpture Day.

This pic is from my last weekend trip to Louisville on Leap Day. What a great time my Mom and I had checking out the art on display at 21c, as well as the Picasso show at KMAC.

Zamora's work was one of many pieces looking at manual labor and its place in society at 21c. The artist has said the sculpture, "Brasil," explores "the weight of a delirious composition of progress.” IMO society has been reckoning with this on many fronts. Last night we performed at the 21c Museum Hotel in Lexington, Kentucky - the first of 5 intermittent performances we’ll be doing with @21chotels this tour. Super cool spot!! The museum is open 24 hours and free the the public - Plus, I’m not gonna lie, having a hotel room in the same building as your performance is basically a touring musician’s biggest dream!! 🙏🏼 We came upon this piece by Frances Goodman (@fjgoodman) - whose work about femininity intersected with “Out There”. Check out the description of her piece. 🙌🏻 We also met an awesome group of artists and friends - in particular Jeanne Vomit-Terror and Long Jumper who also performed. Super fun night!! 💜 next shows 3/17 DC @cometpingpong 3/18 PHILLY @voxpopuligallery 3/19 ROCHESTER @roco137 and 3/29 AMHERST @hampshirecollege !!! .

My tribute to one of my favorite Louisville Kentucky landmarks - #21cmuseumhotel. A free art museum, open 24/7 & boutique hotel! If you visit with me, I will take you there. I love so many aspects of the hotel to the many galleries downstairs, the silver tornado, the video installation room, the falling words of poetry at the elevators, the coolest mens restroom on the planet and downstairs a gym - not just any gym but Madonna worked out in there! We should take a tour together. I’ve gone on Saturday morning yoga surrounded by #kehindewiley artwork. The penguins are a staple at each location, each representing a color of the city, Louisville Stoneware makes small version and I have one from each visit & I’m still collecting, I think I have six. Proof the restaurant within, I should do a separate piece of art just for Proof! If you have been to visit me you have had a bison burger. Ooooohhhh our red penguin, the bird that started it all! #21cmuseumhotel and one of the founders LauraLee make me proud to be from #kentucky. Life feeds us a whole host of emotions and regardless of how beautiful or dismal our physical reality looks, time teaches us that nothing ever stays the same and patience allows us to experience and endure it.” Artist Stephanie Hirsch, featured in The Future is Female at the 21c Museum Hotel in Durham 🎨”Indestructible”, 2016

You’ve probably seen me post stories about Yoga Fest 2020 and fundraising events to support it, but I wanted to shed light on the organization responsible for YF 2020 — Our Yoga Collective. What is it, you ask?

Having a yearly event where the yoga community comes together is great! But we want more. OYC is a collaborative effort to offer continuous support to the yoga community. To new and seasoned yoga teachers, yoga studios, and really anyone who could benefit from a support system! It’s going to be an online platform with SO many offerings. I’d suggest going to ouryogacollective.org to see the full realm of offerings. (Link in bio). This is just the beginning!

First things first, though. YF 2020 is in March! Our first fundraising event is a cake walk this Sunday @elementalcoffee and we’re currently having a 50% flash sale on tickets. That could get you a ticket for $5! This isn’t just for “yogis...” EVERYONE is welcome to come drink a few beers (BYOB) and get a chance to win a locally made cake and other prizes. Ticket price increases at the door. 7pm-9pm, 11/3. 
There’s a lot more announcements to be made (teaching opps at YF & local artists to design our logo) so stay tuned and follow along!

Just up the road in Bentonville is a unique museum and hotel experience.⁣
⁣
21c Museum Hotel in Bentonville is one of eight hotels located in "flyover country" that cater to people who are looking for more than just an adequate bed and hot water.⁣
Throughout the 12,000 square foot property, guests are surrounded by thoughtful and dramatic art installations. The pieces provide something other than the traditional floral or landscape prints to engage with as they walk through the lobby.⁣
⁣
And if you're hungry, The Hive, the onsite restaurant headed up by executive chef and James Beard nominee Matthew McClure, won't disappoint. ⁣
⁣
If you're headed to Northwest Arkansas, definitely take a look! https://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/museum/exhibit/refuge/

Pie + happy hour? Yes please! Our friend @thebubblygirl discovered this Sweet Potato Sour with bourbon in Louisville, Kentucky. Here’s the recipe:

2 oz Four 🌹 Single Barrel Bourbon
1 oz sweet potato pie batter
.75 oz lemon
2 dashes Peychauds bitters
Spritz absinthe or 2 drops
Sprinkle nutmeg
Star anise 
Orange and lemon zest
Add bourbon, sweet potato pie batter, lemon and bitters to a shaker filled with ice. Shake until your hand is really cold. Strain into a rocks glass filled with ice. Garnish with a spritz (or 2 drops) of absinthe, star anise, nutmeg and citrus peels. 🥃🍠🍋

Giving myself the morning off, I decided to sit down with a cup of coffee, listen to some Prokofiev, and read poetry. I needed this: I often overwork myself and skip these needed break days.
.
.
So what to read? Poetry? The Kirkus Review? Thomas Mann? Everything I picked up left me blank.
.
.
From this urge to relax came a sudden and insatiable urge to find something creative to read. Something that would inspire me. But nothing fit. So I decided, in a flash, that I’d create it!
.
.
I decided to write a poem, my quickest and most comfortable craft. In a flurry of wild and exciting energy (i.e. inspiration), I grabbed a writing prompt book I wasn’t using, wrote a poem in blue Sharpie, then outlined it in orange, going back over the words but also using the spaces in which to write more words. And I fucking love it! (I’m showing it in a later post).
.
.
So much energy!
.
.
And if affects your entire life in so many other ways too. Only an hour after creating this work, I felt so energized, so much lighter. I gave people compliments and push them to be more creative and positive in their acts and thoughts. I was drunk off creativity haha! And right before I went in to work, I went into @21cchicago and felt inspired even more. It’s a cycle!
.
.
And remember, if you can’t find what you’re looking for, make something. I like how I couldn’t just sit down in the corner and be “good”. I had to create. And once you tap into that, it’s that simple. To quote the character Lucas from the movie Empire records, who himself quotes Jim Morrison: “the time to hesitate is through”.
.
.
Thank you @chasejarvis for writing your book, Creative Calling, and for giving me the steps to making myself more creative every single day.
.
.
Create and complete!
.
.
.

💗💗 My TOP Hair Tips: 💗💗⁣
⁣
- Stop blow drying it all the dang time, friends. It’s just blowing hot air. ⁣
⁣
- Eat a cupcake every once in awhile. (I have no scientific proof it works, but I have no scientific proof that it doesn’t. 💁🏼‍♀️🧁)⁣
⁣
- STOP wasting your money on fancy, schmancy hair TOOLS. 🛑 Target has just about every tool you’ll ever need for about $30-$50 tops. ( ILY Jen Adkins but $500 hair dryers are for the moms at Christmas who already own just about everything else: @gipsonja) ⁣
⁣
- With that being said, DO invest in some delicious hair PRODUCT. 🧖🏼‍♀️💕 I personally like to juice my hair up with some heavenly shampoo/conditioner/post-shower product and keep my dry shampoos, hair sprays, etc. drug store cheap. ⁣
⁣
- Most importantly, find a hair stylist BFF that cares about your hair just as much (if not more) than you do. 💗💗💗⁣
⁣
And while you’re at it — keep your dollars local. Thankful to be in the hands of so many loving hair friends here in the 417. Especially thankful today for @taliagrace12 & my blowout gals at Studio 417. ⁣
⁣

In October 2018, we lived in Bloomington and both worked at IU. Justin hadn’t picked a law school and I didn’t know what my career might be when we moved. We didn’t know where we would be in a year or what we would be doing. I didn’t worry because I knew we would be doing it together. As expected, everything turned out just fine.

Honestly, I can’t narrow this amazing day down to ten pictures, thanks in part to the amazing work of our #wedding photographers @eastlynandjoshua. So here are some sappy moments with our sweet family to start. (Almost couldn’t fit my ginormous family in the frame.)

Yesterday someone was asking me about inspiration, motivation and then these shoes came up in our conversation! I’d say 90% of my work starts from music, or children’s books - but I’m a fashion lover since birth, too - so it’s natural for me to marry the three! This pair was for an artist couple who are heavily engrained in the @21chotels in Louisville. When I was shown the hotel photos for inspiration, I first packed my bag and said “be right there” and then immediately starting playing with the “kaleidoscope eye” concept, listening to Lucy in the Sky with Diamonds. This pair was born and, to-date, is my least reordered pair, yet the most talked about, most shared, seemingly most loved pair. Swipe to see the hotel rooms that made me GASP and were just begging to be artfully reproduced on baby moccasins for the couples new baby.✨🤟🏻#swipeleft #freerangemama #happyfriday #21cmuseumhotel #stainedglasseffect #lucyintheskywithdiamonds #kaleidoscopeeyes #shoeart #myminnetonka #babymoccasins #babyshoes #handpaintedshoes #inspiration #hotelart #thankful

ARKANSAS - Bentonville:  Day 4 of our Travel with The Met journey... now in the hometown of the Walton’s and Walmart.  Checked into the ultra cool 21c Museum Hotel.  A specialized chain of 8 hotels (with more on the way)... and it truly is a museum within the hotel with dedicated gallery spaces and art everywhere.  Was thrilled to see several works by Cuban artists that I know including friend Alex Hernandez.  Everything is beautifully displayed and labeled, there is a brochure on the collection and they have curator lead tours of the collection. Outside was a classic 1962 Cadillac limousine covered with nickels, dimes and pennies by Monica Mahoney and entitled Making Change.  Also they had a great shop, delicious food in the restaurant and spacious/comfortable rooms.  And right in the center of town and walkable to the Crystal Bridges Museum.  Definitely THE place to stay.  #travelwiththemet #arrangementsabroadtravelwiththemet #arrangementsabroad #21c #21cmuseumhotel #21cbentonville #yoancapote #arrangementsinamerica #chasmiller3travels #chasmiller3travels2019heartland

“Linear Sky” (2018) by Luftwerk
.
One of the best things about coming to Kansas City (besides getting amazing BBQ) are the art galleries and installations. This piece is at the lobby entrance to 21C Museum Hotel. After a 2yr renovation it now features a contemporary art museum. “This piece features light fixtures that vary in length, producing an anamorphic optical illusion of an expanding, outward pattern of line and color upon entering and exiting the ramp. The hues from one direction differ from those in the opposite direction, acting like a multi-colored mirror of each other and differentiating the experience of moving into or out of the hallway.” #luftwerk #luftwerks #linearsky #21cmuseumhotel #contemporaryart #artmuseumhotel #artmuseum #kansascity #kansascityisamazing #loveofart #loveartanddesign #artanddesign

The SuperNatural at 21C Museum Hotel in Nashville - this exhibition, curated by Alice Gray Stites, was first presented in Durham NC - and features works of photography, video and sculpture. “Landscape, once the realm of the bucolic and pastoral, now appears alluring and alarming, fantastical, threatening, and threatens, reflecting the earth’s evolution toward an Anhropocene: a planet whose contours and contents will be defined by human activity.” The exhibition, on three floors, includes numerous artists from the 21C collection.  A full statement is on the 21C website exhibitions page.

Join us @21chotels to celebrate tomorrow! I’m proud to have been a part of this amazing group of women sculptors since 2003. I started out as a sculptor and transitioned to painting - all the while this group has been a source of inspiration and support. We are thrilled to be seeing a banner hung to honor our namesake this weekend! .

Artist Nathaniel Covington launched the Grand Opening of Modfellows Art & Design Gallery with his “Creature Feature / Monster” sculptures, large paintings and papier-mâché masks. 
Nathaniel Covington is constructing bold, colorfully sculpted papier- mâché monster masks and large, pop art creature paintings. His art pieces have simple lines, set against solid color backgrounds. He’s predominately influenced by 1969’s - 1980’s “Creature Feature Films”, horror soundtracks, Sci-Fi magazines and a dash of Ed Roth. For Nathaniel, the process starts with rough sketches on paper, wood, skateboards, just about anything he can draw on, allowing him the vision to finalize the masks and paintings. The making of masks started about 3 years ago and he fell in love with the process. “It’s an opportunity to bring to life all the “Creatures” and wildly funny things living in my head.” He says, “I’d like the art pieces that I make to evoke some sort of emotion when they are seen.” The show will run July 20th - Aug 24th

Equal parts historic & revitalized, the @artsdistrictokc, including @filmrowokc, which was once home to the film distribution offices for Hollywood’s major studios. Now it is home to artistic businesses, locally owned restaurants and more.  We love @thejonesokc both for food and live music and of course @flashbackretropub is a can't miss with 60+ arcade games & pinball machines taking you right back to the 80's, neon & all!

The Arts District is also now home to the @okcmarathon Finish Line!

The @oklahomacitymoa is home to collections of art, including an extensive collection of @chihulystudio glass. One of their current exhibitions is The Mellon Collection of French Art from @vmfamuseum, including works from VAN GOGH, MONET & DEGAS!

Contemporary art is at the heart of the @21chotels Museum Hotel experience with rotating exhibitions, always FREE to the public, even if you’re not staying overnight. 
Performing arts at the heart of @okcciviccenter, home to the @okc_phil, @okcballet & @okcbroadway.

There’s so much to see & do and no telling who you might run into crossing the street! 🦆 
Summer is the perfect time to explore this beautiful part of our city! What’s your favorite spot in the @artsdistrictokc? 💙

I know I should have probably been posting pictures of my practice quilts from my #modernquiltmasters workshop with Jacquie Gering ... but I’ve been so immersed in (and exhausted by!) the workshop that the time is just flying by, so I have quickly collaged a few of the samples for you to see (swipe left). If you follow me, you know I’m passionate about #domesticmachinequilting - and this is upping my game even further. Two more days to go, and the atmosphere of creativity here is just so powerful here. We are privileged to be previewing all of the designs and methods from Jacquie’s new book “Walk 2.0,” which debuts at QuiltCon in February (preorder is available on Amazon now). .
.
We are at the @21chotels in downtown Kansas City. It’s a gorgeous hotel with modern art (all created in the 21st century, with most of the artists still living) in the rooms, and otherwise around every turn. Plus, there are these giant blue penguin sculptures throughout the hotel that get moved around throughout the day. I was just tickled that this fellow was waiting for me at my door when I returned to my room. They do show up in the oddest places! .
.
.
With only a dozen students, everyone is completely immersed in the learning, and Jacquie is like the energizer bunny of teachers. I honestly don’t know how she’s doing it. We are sewing on machines provided by @berninausa and while I’ve been a loyal @janomeamerica sewist for many years, I’m kind if in love with the Bernina 570QE. Yum!..
.
.
(Don’t look too closely at the starts and stops on my little letter “E” quilt. I’ve done the negative space letters once before, but I was really focusing here on the beautiful 1/8” line spacing I could get -without marking!- with the Bernina walking foot, so my starts and stops suffered a bit. I love the look, though, and will definitely be revisiting the technique when I can spend more time on the detail. It’s REAL matchstick quilting, LOL!).
.
.

I recently discovered that I have a piece up at the University of Memphis Art Museum in an exhibit called Dear Artist, in which the collectors write the artist a letter ✉️
Thanks to the Havners for the wonderful words, it really made my day. 🙏🙌 #repost from @artmuseum_um 
Lisa Alonzo (American, b. 1984)
Canned Corn Series #13 (Coors can), 2014
Acrylic paint and handmade roses on panel
From the collection of Galen and Debi Havner

Dear Lisa,

We were enjoying the art galleries in the 21C Hotel in Bentonville, Arkansas and came across your works that included Coke, Budweiser, and Red Bull cans. At first it struck as a play on Warhol. When we looked closer we noticed your unique way of applying acrylic paint! It was the first time we had ever seen anything like this and were intrigued. We contacted art dealer friend, David Lusk, who was able to find your Coors can at the Claire Oliver Studio in NYC. We love your theme of the various drink cans and the name of the series, The Canned Corn Set.

I know you must be a fabulous baker of beautifully decorated cakes, judging by the way you used the pastry sleeve as your brush for your art. Our personal collection also includes your larger piece of work, Bravery Test. It brings the meaning of pointillism to new heights. The snowy mountains and their reflection on the lake would test a climber’s resolve. We enjoy having your work in our home. They are always a source of great conversations with our guests.

Thank you for your inspiration.

#art #dearartist @uofmemphis #coorslight#cake #lisaalonzo

LK is leaving 💔💔💔💔 Cannot even believe it’s already time to put him on a plane back to Germany. ⁣
⁣
Lucky for me, I’ll be kicking it in the US a bit longer to hang with my fam & friends. ⁣
⁣
We have been beyond thankful for this time together in the States & I know he’ll be going back home a bit more relaxed, suntanned & heavier (shoutout to all of the delicious, local food we’ve been consuming the past few weeks 😍). 🍦🍿🍻🍔🌮🍟🍕🍛⁣
⁣
The #1 question we get when we travel to the US is: “What are you going to eat first?!”⁣
But more important for us is: WHAT are we going to eat LAST?! ⁣
⁣
So while y’all are enjoying your Monday afternoon, we’ll be arguing about what he wants for lunch tomorrow for the next 24 hours. 😂💗⁣
⁣

[ad]⁣ My little family is kicking off summer the best way we know how: surrounded by the beauty of nature and immersing ourselves in art!⁣

We came to my neck of the woods (Northwest Arkansas) to explore @CrystalBridgesMuseum & other amazing things that Bentonville, AR has to offer. And I’m sure y’all have heard me talking about architecture being my first love, and Crystal Bridges is winning in that department. The museum blends with nature so effortlessly 😍 I haven’t visited since 2012, so I’m ready to discover all of the wonders it holds again. And we’ll be jamming out at the kick off of the Forest Concert Series. We have so many fun things to do, and I’ll be posting about them all, so get ready to add Bentonville & Crystal Bridges to your summer bucket list 😆💚⁣

Spent the day in #Cincinnati yesterday for a workshop hosted by #InfoTrust...a group I've worked with on some #retailmarketing projects.  It was great to get expert legal and technical perspectives on consumer data protection laws from people who have a front seat to the developments, and are actually creating solutions for implementation.  We've done well protecting out clients, but thanks to 45 and Cambridge Analytica, these laws are going to keep coming, so my job is to it's know what's happening before it happens. ...And the bonus was all of the cool art on display at Cinci's #21cmuseumhotel.  Took me back to my hotel days. I loved working in beautiful environments like this. Well...maybe not like THIS, but close? Lol

Welcome to downtown Durham American Tobacco district where entertainment, restaurants, breweries, boutique hotels, condos and baseball meet up. DPAC theater has entertainment from Broadway shows like Hamilton, Youtubers like Game Grumps, comedians such as Jerry Seinfeld & Jay Leno, performers like The Indigo Girls, Impractical Jokers and so many other great talents. 
If visiting Durham, then stay right there at Aloft or downtown a few blocks at The Durham Hotel, 21c Museum Hotel, Unscripted Durham, Marriott, with night life rooftop bars and pools with a view. Eat before the show at Nana Steak or any of the fabulous restaurants downtown Durham!

Price Harrison earned a Bachelor's Degree in English and Fine Arts at Vanderbilt University in 1984. He studied architecture at Yale University where he earned a Master's Degree. In 1987 he began an apprenticeship in New York with the late Paul Rudolph. After studying with Mr. Rudolph, Harrison went on to work with Richard Meier and Partners, Pei Cobb Freed, and George Ranalli.

In 1998 Harrison returned to Nashville where he founded his firm Price Harrison Architect and Associates PLLC.

Women Artist Wednesday: ENID member Leticia R. Bajuyo! She is a sculptor who uses namable, seemingly neutral, commonplace icons and objects to animate theatrical re-arbitrations of value. Her sculptures and installations have been exhibited nationally including large-scale public art installations in the Tony Hillerman Library (Albuquerque, New Mexico); the Indiana State Museum (Indianapolis); the Lyon Square outdoor plaza (Grand Rapids, Michigan); and the South Bend Museum of Art. Recent international exhibitions include FRAME OF MIND 2016, a Northern Mindanao Contemporary Art exhibit in Mindanao, Philippines and the 2015 IV International From Waste to Art Exhibition in Baku, Azerbaijan. Bajuyo received her M.F.A. in 2001 from the University of Tennessee, Knoxville and her B.F.A. in 1998 from the University of Notre Dame. Currently, Bajuyo resides, teaches, and makes art in Indiana while she is a visiting faculty member at the University of Notre Dame. Additionally, Bajuyo is a member of the Board of Directors for the National Performance Network and Visual Arts Network (NPNVAN), and is a member of the Board of Governors for the Speed Museum, Louisville, Kentucky. 
See Bajuyo along with other ENID members at the Gallery Talk with the Artists of Interwoven this Thursday, June 6th at 21c Museum Hotel Louisville (6pm). The exhibition Interwoven: A Tribute to Enid Yandell is on display at  @21chotels until October 2019.  Pictured here is Bajuyo's piece for the exhibit - Hypergrass: Triple, 2018. Corey Lee Schultz - Cancer Survivor Story: Scalp Cooling- (go to our Facebook page for the full speech) Thank you to Baptist Health and Greg Bodager (BH Cancer Center Director) for being pioneers of scalp cooling in central Kentucky. LCF is honored to support the Paxman scalp cooling program at Baptist Health. With all of the physical and mental stress of the cancer journey, to lighten the burden of losing your hair can help make all the difference. We want to make this affordable for everyone, it is not covered by insurance. Listen to Corey’s journey. Thank you Baptist Health for your vision and support of LCF.

Corey Lee Schultz, sponsor and friend of LCF, had the courage to tell her personal story (that is directly related to one of our grant awards) at our Grant Awards Luncheon, this past Thursday, March 28 at the 21C Museum Hotel. 
LCF is honored to celebrate 15 years of raising funds for cancer patients and their families. The stories of survivors, families, our grantees and more, need to be heard - we will be sharing them with you.

A highlight of my trip to Cincinnati for the Society of American Travel Writers conference was staying at my second 21c Museum Hotel. If you haven’t stayed at one yet, do it! There are 8 with 3 “coming soon” mostly in the middle of the country. Each is an art museum first, hotel second... making for a unique experience involving #penguins. From the chandelier out front to a front desk made of thousands of miniature human figures to your shower tiles to rotating exhibits that fill several floors of the hotel - you will find art everywhere! We had a chance to meet and interview 21c co-founder Steve Wilson (third photo) - what an amazing journey he’s had. He says the museum hotels are a way to share the art he and his wife have collected for the past 25 years. He describes the collection, which continues to grow, as the art of now. #satw #satwcincy #cincyexperience #21cmuseumhotel @21chotels

COMMUNITY: Portia Munson Gatherings Reflect on Our Culture ⭐️ Watch the full 📺 on Daily Plinth ⭐️ Link in Bio - Follow us for daily art world videos ⭐️ Of the many highlights in the fantastic new Meridians section at Art Basel Miami Beach this year is the installation 'The Garden' (1996) by artist Portia Munson. Brought down and offered for sale by the inimitable P.P.O.W. gallery on something of a-wing-and-a-prayer, we were thrilled to hear that it sold on the first day!⠀
⠀
In the fall of 2018, Munson was featured in a solo exhibition at the Bedford Gallery at the Lesher Center for the Arts in Walnut Creek, California, 'Portia Munson: Her Room/Her World.' A centerpiece of the exhibition was an accumulation installation similar to 'The Garden,' entitled 'Pink Room' (1994-2018) consisting of thousands of pink-colored castoff objects. In this video from the Bedford Gallery, Munson discusses her installation and how her work addresses issues of feminism and environmentalism.⠀

Join Miranda Lash, Curator of Contemporary Art at the Speed Art Museum, and Alice Gray Stites, @21chotels Chief Curator and Museum Director, co-curators of the exhibition, for a final gallery talk on August 31 at 2pm at the Speed Art Museum.

To all the “weirdos” in life that see the world in a different way and find creative ways to express it, keep doing what you do!  So people like me, that don’t/won’t/can’t create, have the chance to learn about and appreciate your perception of the world. You give us culture and self awareness that we often refuse to acknowledge. It’s not that we don’t care or want to know, we have yet to unlock that space in our brain. Keep creating uncomfortable moments, images, and art so we will continue to learn and step outside of our self imposed boundaries. #21cmuseumhotel 👩🏼‍🎨👨🏾‍🎨🖼

🍵Today I had the honor of experiencing a traditional Japanese Tea Ceremony with Tea Master, Yumie Farringer, accompanied by her student, Fumie Horne. 
Due to the nature of the ceremony I thought it best not to take any photos during and instead enjoy the moment and rare opportunity not many in Oklahoma get to experience. It was a beautiful ceremony. 😌
All of these photos are from after the ceremony when we were enjoying a tea and snack tasting. ☺️ We even got to make our own cups of tea with their guidance, which was a new experience for me and very fun!
Thank you very much to Yumie, Fumie, @japansocietyok and @21chotels for such a lovely event 🍵

I am thrilled that Chastity Cyia from the series Dazzling is currently up at the 21c Museum Hotel in conjunction with the exhibition “The Future is Female”. The exhibition was curated by Alice Gray Stites Chief Curator and Museum Director with work by artists Zoe Buckman, Zanele Muholi, Saya Woolfalk, Alison Saar, and Stephanie Hirsch to name a few.
The 21c Museum Hotels was founded by Laura Lee Brown and Steve Wilson, contemporary art collectors who are committed to the power of art and want their collection to have a public presence. After a visit to Birmingham with the Whitney Museum of Art support group they purchased six photographs from Dazzling to be part of their permanent collection. I am thrilled that this photograph is installed at 21c in Bentonville, Arkansas and will be up until September 15, 2019. I will have to make a trip! 
21c Hotels is America’s first museum dedicated solely to collecting and exhibiting the art of the 21st century. The museum has eight locations with over 75,000 square feet of exhibition space. 21c presents curated exhibitions and site-specific installations that reflect the global nature of today.
 As always, thanks to Guido Maus and Beta Pictoris Gallery
